        "description": {
            "name": "description",
            "type": "java.lang.String",
            "value": "The usage of Zend_Translate_Adapter::$_languages in concomitance of the Zend_Translate_Adapter_Tmx adapter can be cause of dictionary inconsistence with translate(), isTranslated(), getMessages(), getMessageIds() ...\nThis is the scenery:\n{code}\n$locale = new Zend_Locale(Zend_Locale::BROWSER) ;\n\/\/ or\n$locale = \"it\" ;\n\/\/ is the same\n$translate = new Zend_Translate(\"Tmx\", \"file.tmx\", $locale) ;\n{code}\n\nfile.tmx\n{code}\n<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<!DOCTYPE tmx SYSTEM \"tmx14.dtd\">\n<tmx version=\"1.4\">\n    <header\/>\n    <body>\n        <tu tuid=\"message_id1\">\n            <tuv xml:lang=\"en\"><seg>good morning<\/seg><\/tuv>\n            <tuv xml:lang=\"fr\"><seg>bonjour<\/seg><\/tuv>\n        <\/tu>\n    <\/body>\n<\/tmx>\n{code}\nWith current approach we have this problem:\n{code}\nvar_dump($translate->getList()) ;\nvar_dump($translate->getMessages()) ; \/\/ or anything that returns Zend_Translate_Adapter::$_translate \/*  ZF-1937 *\/\n{code}\n\n{code}\narray(3) {\n    [\"it\"] => string(2) \"it\"\n    [\"en\"] => string(2) \"en\"\n    [\"fr\"] => string(2) \"fr\"\n}\narray(2) {\n    [\"en\"] => array(1) {\n        \"message_id1\"] => string(12) \"good morning\"\n    }\n    [\"fr\"] => array(1) {\n        [\"message_id1\"] => string(12) \"bonjour\"\n    }\n}\n{code}\nThis difference is cause of many problems.\n{code}\n$translate->isAvailable(\"it\"); \/\/ return true\n\/* this is wrong: there is nothing to translate with \"it\" so this should not be present *\/\n\n$translate->isTranslated(\"message_id1\"); \/\/ return false\n$translate->_(\"message_id1\"); \/\/ return \"message_id1\"\n\/* these two actions return correct results and I think that they are the only methods to do the correct check *\/\n\n$translate->getMessages() ; \/\/ return null ;\n$translate->getMessageIds() ; \/\/ return null ;\n\/* Both raise a notice of \"Undefined index\" (Zend_Translate_Adapter::$_translate[\"it\"]) *\/\n\/* \"it\" is the default locale but it isn't present in Zend_Translate_Adapter::$_translate *\/\n\/* This is wrong *\/\n{code}\n\nI think that the problem is in Zend_Translate_Adapter::$_languages.\nIt may contain languages that aren't translated and this is not correct.\nFor this reason Zend_Translate_Adapter::(isAvailable|getMessages|MessageIds|setLocale|addTranslation)() are bugged.\n\nThis is an example of a bad check:\n(isAvailable|setLocale)()\n{code}\nif (! in_array($locale, $this->_languages))\n...\n{code}\n\nThis is an example of  a good check:\n(isTranslated|translate)()\n{code}\nif (array_key_exists($locale, $this->_translate))\n...\n{code}\nI think that the Zend_Translate_Adapter::$_languages property should be removed in favour of the Zend_Translate_Adapter::getLocales() method:\n{code}\npublic function getLocales()\n{\n    return array_keys($this->_translate) ;\n}\n{code}\n\nin this way the correct check can be performed with :\n{code}\nif (array_key_exists($locale, $this->_translate))\n\/\/ or\nif (in_array($locale, $this->getLocales())\n{code}\n\nZend_Translate_Adapter::getLocales() must be the substitute of Zend_Translate_Adapter::getList() that should be fixxed and deprecated. Furthermore, I think that the method name \"getLocales\" is more correct than \"getList\".\n\nTHERE IS NO BREAK OF COMPATIBILITY WITH THIS FIX"
        },
